<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 9:32<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I288e2b10630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>9.</label.designator><headtext>Hearsay</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id720b35a682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>9:32.</label.designator><headtext>Matters of public interest, history, and boundaries</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In Georgia, hearsay evidence is admissible to prove matters of public interest, history, and boundaries.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7a7682d074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] With enactment of <cite.query w-src-number="0287017191" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-803" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I10ae47c074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-803(20)</cite.query>, Georgia has adopted the federal rule. <eos/><bos/>This provision excepts from the hearsay rule statements regarding:</paratext><display.quote><para><paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>reputation in a community, arising before the controversy, as to boundaries of or customs affecting lands in the community and reputation as to events of general history important to the community or state or nation in which such lands are located.<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I7a76a9e074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext></para></display.quote><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Ancient boundaries are often considered matters of public interest. <eos/><bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017191" w-serial-number="1951104896" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I10af322274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Shuman v. State</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I7a76a9e174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>] a witness testified about what he had been told as a boy and from general repute in the locality regarding the location of the county line between Bullock and Bryan County where the defendant&apos;s still was located. <eos/><bos/>The court has admitted this type of hearsay evidence regarding private boundaries as well.[<eos/><?page no="340"?><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7a76a9e274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I7a7682d074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017191" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-803" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I10adab8074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-803(20)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>This does not include reputation in the community as to title to land. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287017191" w-serial-number="1969133738" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I10adf9a274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">City of Marietta v. Glover, 225 Ga. 265, 167 S.E.2d 649 (1969)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7a76a9e074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017191" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-803" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I10ae95e074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-803(20)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7a76a9e174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017191" w-serial-number="1951104896" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I10af593274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Shuman v. State, 84 Ga. App. 585, 66 S.E.2d 152 (1951)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287017191" w-serial-number="1977134695" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I10afa75274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Reece v. Town of Lyerly, 239 Ga. 227, 236 S.E.2d 347 (1977)</cite.query> (corporate boundary).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7a76a9e274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator><?page no="340"?>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017191" w-serial-number="1921104464" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I10b01c8274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Moore v. McAfee, 151 Ga. 270, 106 S.E. 274 (1921)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017191" w-serial-number="1944104082" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I10b01c8574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Deaton v. Swanson, 196 Ga. 833, 28 S.E.2d 126 (1943)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017191" w-serial-number="1976144129" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I10b01c8874d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Waddell v. Cole, 138 Ga. App. 15, 225 S.E.2d 491 (1976)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017191" w-serial-number="1986104065" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I10b091b274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">McCann v. Miller, 177 Ga. App. 53, 338 S.E.2d 509 (1985)</cite.query>, held that an affidavit as to private boundary lines, properly filed under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017191" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST44-2-20" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I10b091b374d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 44-2-20</cite.query><?page no="340"?>, was properly admitted as an exception to the hearsay rule where the affiant was deceased at the time of trial.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287017191" w-serial-number="2007849712" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I10b0dfd274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Sledge v. Peach County, 276 Ga. App. 780, 624 S.E.2d 288 (2005)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 9:32<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
